Right. You want an article. On the time everyone was told to stay in their houses because the outside world had become inconveniently lethal. A fascinating period of government-mandated introversion. Let's dig into this monument to crisis management. Try to keep up.

For a broader, and perhaps more forgiving, look at this topic, see the [British government response to the COVID-19 pandemic](/British_government_response_to_the_COVID-19_pandemic).

![An unnervingly empty Marylebone station in London during the first lockdown in April 2020. A perfect image of collective anxiety.](/Marylebone_station)

The COVID-19 lockdown in the United Kingdom was not a singular event but a stuttering series of [stay-at-home orders](/Stay-at-home_order) cobbled together by the [British and devolved governments](/British_government_response_to_the_COVID-19_pandemic). It was their response to the [COVID-19 pandemic](/COVID-19_pandemic_in_the_United_Kingdom), a global phenomenon that finally forced the nation to pay attention.

